üß™ Example Program: Compare for vs while

# Print numbers from 1 to 5 using both for and while loops. Then, keep asking the user to enter a number until they enter a positive number.

import java.util.Scanner;

public class LoopComparison {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        // 1Ô∏è‚É£ Using FOR loop when number of iterations is known
        System.out.println("Using for loop to print numbers 1 to 5:");
        for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
            System.out.println("Number: " + i);
        }

        // 2Ô∏è‚É£ Using WHILE loop when the condition is uncertain
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);
        int number;

        System.out.println("\nEnter a positive number:");
        number = scanner.nextInt();

        while (number <= 0) {
            System.out.println("You entered " + number + ". Please enter a positive number:");
            number = scanner.nextInt();
        }

        System.out.println("Thank you! You entered a positive number: " + number);
        scanner.close();
    }
}



================================== üß† Explanation ====================================================================

=======================================================================================================================


üü© Part 1 ‚Äì for loop:

    We know we want to print numbers from 1 to 5 (5 times).

    Perfect case for for loop.

üü¶ Part 2 ‚Äì while loop:

    We don‚Äôt know how many times the user might enter wrong input.

    So, we keep asking until they give a positive number.

    Perfect use case for while loop.

=======================================================================================================================
=======================================================================================================================


| Use `for` loop when...                                                      | Use `while` loop when...                                                     |
| --------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| You **know in advance** how many times to loop (fixed number of iterations) | You **don‚Äôt know** how many times to loop (loop until some condition is met) |
| Loop counter is used                                                        | Waiting for a condition, user input, or unknown event                        |
